Create a GitHub Repository:

Log in to GitHub.
Click the "+" button, choose "New repository".
Give it a name, description, and choose if it's public or private.
Click "Create repository".
Clone the Repository:

After creating, copy its web address.
Open your terminal or command prompt.
Use a command to copy the repository to your computer.
Make Changes:

Find the folder on your computer where the repository was copied.
Change the files using a writing tool.
Stage the Changes:

Prepare the changes you made to be saved.
Commit the Changes:

Save the changes with a short description.
Push Changes to the Remote Repository:

Send your saved changes back to GitHub.